WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.800 --> 00:00:06.455
Let's look inside a single run.

2
00:00:06.455 --> 00:00:11.766
First, the planner reads your task and produces a detailed design document.

3
00:00:11.766 --> 00:00:17.520
Next, an optional plan reviewer audits that plan, before any code is written.

4
00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:19.733
Then the coordinator takes over.

5
00:00:19.733 --> 00:00:23.716
It breaks the plan into small units of work.

6
00:00:23.716 --> 00:00:25.929
We call those units beads.

7
00:00:25.929 --> 00:00:28.584
Each bead gets a complexity tag.

8
00:00:28.584 --> 00:00:33.452
Now one or more implementer agents pick up beads in parallel.

9
00:00:33.452 --> 00:00:37.878
Each one writes the code and tests for its slice.

10
00:00:37.878 --> 00:00:41.419
After that, a tester runs the full suite.

11
00:00:41.419 --> 00:00:43.632
A reviewer audits the diff.

12
00:00:43.632 --> 00:00:49.385
Only then does the guardian commit the work and open the pull request.

13
00:00:49.385 --> 00:00:55.581
Finally, an optional learner extracts insights from the run, so future runs can improve.

14
00:00:57.381 --> 00:00:59.564
Pipelines also define the guardrails.

15
00:00:59.564 --> 00:01:02.183
How many review rounds are allowed?

16
00:01:02.183 --> 00:01:03.929
How many test retries?

17
00:01:03.929 --> 00:01:08.294
How much can a single run cost before it halts?

18
00:01:08.294 --> 00:01:11.787
All these limits live in the pipeline definition.

19
00:01:11.787 --> 00:01:17.025
So the same template enforces the same discipline every time it runs.

20
00:01:18.825 --> 00:01:21.893
Here's the part that makes worca trustworthy.

21
00:01:21.893 --> 00:01:23.646
Governance is not advice.

22
00:01:23.646 --> 00:01:25.399
It's enforced at runtime.

23
00:01:25.399 --> 00:01:30.220
worca installs hooks that gate every tool call and every commit.

24
00:01:30.220 --> 00:01:32.850
The planner cannot write source files.

25
00:01:32.850 --> 00:01:34.603
The implementer cannot commit.

26
00:01:34.603 --> 00:01:40.301
Only the guardian can commit, and only after the reviewer has signed off.

27
00:01:40.301 --> 00:01:46.875
The pipeline cannot drift off process, no matter what the underlying model decides to do.

28
00:01:48.675 --> 00:01:50.727
When things fail, worca self-corrects.

29
00:01:50.727 --> 00:01:57.704
If tests fail, the tester sends the failure back to the implementer, and the implementer tries again.

30
00:01:57.704 --> 00:02:02.218
The same thing happens with review feedback and with plan revisions.

31
00:02:02.218 --> 00:02:05.501
Each loop has a maximum number of iterations.

32
00:02:05.501 --> 00:02:10.426
A circuit breaker watches for patterns that suggest the loop won't converge.

33
00:02:10.426 --> 00:02:15.761
When it sees one, it halts the run before more budget is wasted.

34
00:02:15.761 --> 00:02:17.813
There's also a smarter dial.

35
00:02:17.813 --> 00:02:23.969
If a task keeps looping back, the next pass runs at a higher reasoning level.

36
00:02:23.969 --> 00:02:26.431
Up to a cap you set.

37
00:02:28.231 --> 00:02:30.289
Cost is a real concern.

38
00:02:30.289 --> 00:02:32.758
Every stage logs what it spent.

39
00:02:32.758 --> 00:02:35.227
Every run rolls up a total.

40
00:02:35.227 --> 00:02:38.931
You can see all of it in the UI.

41
00:02:38.931 --> 00:02:41.400
But visibility alone is not enough.

42
00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:44.693
worca gives you three ways to control spend.

43
00:02:44.693 --> 00:02:47.162
The first is the effort cap.

44
00:02:47.162 --> 00:02:50.454
It bounds how high reasoning effort can escalate.

45
00:02:50.454 --> 00:02:52.924
The second is the circuit breaker.

46
00:02:52.924 --> 00:02:58.685
It halts a run when failure patterns suggest you're throwing good money after bad.

47
00:02:58.685 --> 00:03:01.155
The third is the model profile.

48
00:03:01.155 --> 00:03:04.035
You choose which model runs each stage.

49
00:03:04.035 --> 00:03:06.505
Use Opus where you need depth.

50
00:03:06.505 --> 00:03:08.974
Use Sonnet where you need speed.

51
00:03:08.974 --> 00:03:12.678
Route through your own gateway if you have one.

52
00:03:12.678 --> 00:03:18.851
So the question of how much a run will cost becomes a budget you set.

53
00:03:20.651 --> 00:03:24.651
Every action and every artifact is traceable.

54
00:03:24.651 --> 00:03:29.795
The worca-ui web interface gives you the full picture.

55
00:03:29.795 --> 00:03:30.937
Stage progression.

56
00:03:30.937 --> 00:03:31.509
Iterations.

57
00:03:31.509 --> 00:03:32.652
Time spent.

58
00:03:32.652 --> 00:03:33.223
Cost.

59
00:03:33.223 --> 00:03:34.366
Tool calls.

60
00:03:34.366 --> 00:03:36.652
Agent prompts and responses.

61
00:03:36.652 --> 00:03:41.224
Nothing the pipeline does is hidden from you.

62
00:03:43.024 --> 00:03:47.101
Let's get specific about what you can do in the UI.

63
00:03:47.101 --> 00:03:49.324
You can read the generated plan.

64
00:03:49.324 --> 00:03:52.660
You can see how it evolved across review iterations.

65
00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:56.366
You can open any stage and read its agent prompt.

66
00:03:56.366 --> 00:04:00.072
You can also read the dynamic message that agent received.

67
00:04:00.072 --> 00:04:04.889
In other words, you see exactly what worca asked the agent to do.

68
00:04:04.889 --> 00:04:07.854
You can browse the beads the coordinator produced.

69
00:04:07.854 --> 00:04:11.931
You can read the reviewer's verdict and the diff it reviewed.

70
00:04:11.931 --> 00:04:16.748
You can see test output from every iteration, not just the last one.

71
00:04:16.748 --> 00:04:20.825
Cost, time, and tool-call counts are all there, stage by stage.
